In her speech at the Atlantic Council, the U.S. Deputy National Security Advisor, Elizabeth Sherwood-Randall, highlighted the need for the U.S. counterterrorism policy to evolve as the terrorist landscape changes. She outlined three core counterterrorism principles developed by the Biden administration: adapting to the evolving threats, integrating counterterrorism into broader national security priorities, and using a range of tools including diplomacy, development, and prevention efforts. Sherwood-Randall emphasized the importance of partnerships, both international and domestic, in countering terrorism. She also discussed the need to address the threat of domestic terrorism and strengthen prevention efforts through education and community-based approaches. Sherwood-Randall concluded by emphasizing the importance of staying true to American values and leading the world in advancing freedom and democracy.